    <div class="breakhere"></div>

    <article class="page-1" style="padding-top: 100px; padding-bottom: 100px;">
        <h1 class="text-title" style="font-weight: 600; color: #03a7a0;">Introduction</h1>
        <p>
            The Cognitive Aptitude tests measures ability or aptitude to work quickly with numbers, written information and abstract information, such as shapes and patterns. Research has shown that these cognitive
            abilities are important to success in many types of role and industry and that individuals who score higher
            on these tests are likely to be more successful in their role and perform at a higher level than individuals
            who score lower.
        </p>
        <p>
            Specifically, the test measures:
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>
                اNumerical Aptitude –
            </strong> the ability to analyse numerical data in tables and charts, and to perform basic
            mathematical calculations to determine the correct answer
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong> Verbal Aptitude –  </strong>the ability to evaluate and interpret written information and to draw the right conclusions based on passages of text.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Abstract Aptitude – </strong> the ability to analyse patterns and sequences of information, such as shapes and
            diagrams, to solve problems and draw logical conclusions based on these.
        </p>

        <p>
            The candidate’s results have been compared to a group of UAE Nationals who have completed this test
            before.
            Candidate scores are presented in terms of the percentage of the comparison group they scored higher
            than. Both individual tests scores and an overall score for all three tests is given. Since the tests are timed,
            the candidate’s speed when answering the questions is taken into account and impacts their overall and
            individual test scores. The results are likely to remain valid for around 12-18 months.
        </p>

        <p>
            The report covers the following sections:

        </p>

        <p>
            Section 1: Overall and Individual Test Scores
        </p>
    </article>

